      textEn: [
        "Around the Mid-Autumn Festival, it was the season when the osmanthus trees bloomed in my hometown.",
        "As a child, I didn\u2019t know how to appreciate any kind of flower. Father would point them out: this is a plum blossom, that is a magnolia\u2026 but beyond remembering names, I wasn\u2019t interested. What I loved was the osmanthus. The osmanthus tree looked clumsy, unlike the graceful plum tree. When not in bloom, you\u2019d see nothing but leaves; in bloom, you had to search carefully among the branches to spot the tiny flowers. But the fragrance of osmanthus was irresistible.",
        "My hometown was near the sea, and August was typhoon season. As soon as the osmanthus blossomed, Mother began to worry: \u2018Don\u2019t let a typhoon come!\u2019 Every day she\u2019d walk through the front and back yards, murmuring: \u2018As long as there\u2019s no typhoon, I can gather several baskets \u2014 one for Grandpa Hu, one for Granny Mao; their families make lots of cakes.\u2019",
        "When the osmanthus was in full bloom, if not \u2018a fragrance floating ten miles,\u2019 at least a dozen neighboring families all around were immersed in its scent. When the blossoms were ripe, it was time to shake the tree. The shaken-down flowers were each intact and fresh. If left to bloom past their prime and fall into the mud, especially if blown down by wind, the fragrance was much diminished.",
        "Shaking the tree was a big event for me. I\u2019d pester Mother: \u2018Mom, when are we going to shake the osmanthus?\u2019 Mother would say, \u2018Not yet \u2014 the bloom time is too short; they won\u2019t shake off.\u2019 But once she saw the sky filled with dark clouds and knew a typhoon was coming, she\u2019d quickly call everyone to shake the trees early. I was thrilled, hugging the osmanthus trunk and shaking hard. Shake, shake, shake \u2014 the blossoms fell like rain, covering our heads and bodies. I shouted: \u2018Oh! It\u2019s really like rain \u2014 such fragrant rain!\u2019",
        "After the blossoms were shaken off, we\u2019d pick out twigs and leaves, dry them in the sun for a few days, and store them in a tin. They could be added to tea leaves for brewing, or used for making cakes at New Year. All year long, the entire village was immersed in the fragrance of osmanthus.",
        "When I was in middle school, the whole family moved to Hangzhou. There was a hill there covered entirely with osmanthus trees \u2014 when in bloom, the fragrance truly did float ten miles. In autumn, I\u2019d often go there to enjoy the blossoms. Coming home, I\u2019d always bring a large bag of osmanthus for Mother. But Mother said, \u2018No matter how fragrant the osmanthus here, it can\u2019t compare with the osmanthus from our yard back home.\u2019",
        "And so, I think again of the joy of shaking the trees in my childhood home, and of that rain of osmanthus blossoms falling all around."
      ],
