      textEn:[
        "We children found everything fascinating, yet were always unsatisfied. On that Mid-Autumn night, we waited in the courtyard for the moon, but it didn\u2019t appear for a long time, so we went back inside, lowered the bamboo blinds, and pestered Grandma for stories.",
        "Grandma suddenly said: \u2018The moon has come in!\u2019 We looked and sure enough, there in the bamboo blind was the moon, silently gliding in, appearing on the dressing mirror by the window. The moon had grown legs! It climbed the bamboo slats\u2014first a white line, then a half-circle, climbing higher and higher until the mirror held a perfect full orb.",
        "We all ran outside, and there it was in the courtyard. White light everywhere\u2014jade-like, silver. In the center of the courtyard stood the thick old osmanthus tree, with sparse branches and sparse leaves; the blossoms hadn\u2019t opened yet, but it was full of budding clusters.",
        "Grandma said: \u2018The moon belongs to everyone. It hasn\u2019t gone\u2014go find it.\u2019 More curious than ever, we searched the courtyard. Marvelously, it really hadn\u2019t left\u2014we soon found it on grape leaves, on the porcelain flower pot, on Grandpa\u2019s spade blade.",
        "Outside the gate was a small river. The water was shallow, spreading over a wide stretch of clean sand. My brother, standing at the upper bend, shouted: \u2018The moon is here!\u2019 My sister called out almost simultaneously from the lower bend: \u2018The moon is here!\u2019 I went to look at both spots, and both had the moon in the water. Then I noticed tiny moons in my brother\u2019s and sister\u2019s eyes.",
        "Oh, there were so many moons\u2014as long as you wanted one, there it was. We looked up at the moon in the sky, white and luminous overhead. I suddenly felt that since we had the moon, the boundless sky was ours too."
      ],
